@dailydotdev @TwitterSpaces @OpenAI @OfficialLoganK @sherwinwu @nataliestaud Q: What is the plan for business features/products with ChatGPT? 
A: No immediate plans for additional offerings. But please share your use cases with the team. They're always looking for feedback.

@dailydotdev @TwitterSpaces @OpenAI @OfficialLoganK @sherwinwu @nataliestaud Q: How much can we customize ChatGPT to create better answers for our specific use case? How much training is needed?
A: Top of mind for a lot of devs. Generally 3 ways:
1. Prompt engineering - manipulate prompt context
2. Fine Tuning (older models)
3. Info retrieval w/embeddings

@dailydotdev @TwitterSpaces @OpenAI @OfficialLoganK @sherwinwu @nataliestaud Q: How does ChatGPT handle different language idioms? Will this improve in the future?
A: Currently best in English. Most of the corpus is in English, but there is a lot of data in other languages. There are papers available that showcase how it does in other languages.

@dailydotdev @TwitterSpaces @OpenAI @OfficialLoganK @sherwinwu @nataliestaud Q: From a dev perspective, what are the challenges of using ChatGPT?

A: No API yet! But there is demand here.

Also, knowing how far the models can be pushed.

Internet users trained for single attempt approach, but pushing and iterating will improve your efforts.

@dailydotdev @TwitterSpaces @OpenAI @OfficialLoganK @sherwinwu @nataliestaud Q: What's the difference between all these things: @OpenAI API, ChatGPT, GPT-3?

A: The API is a product allowing anyone to make calls against the GPT-3 and GPT-3.5 models directly and build products on top of it. 

ChatGPT is a product built on top of that.

GPT-3 is the model.

@dailydotdev @TwitterSpaces @OpenAI @OfficialLoganK @sherwinwu @nataliestaud Q: What is the difference between GPT-3.5 and previous models or other LLMs?
A: It's really scale. GPT-3.5 came out in March adding a bunch of fine-tuning and training, which is what really enables ChatGPT. Docs include explanation of further details.
